 data sets (patients older than 75) and local data series that we the risks of high doses of radiation and chemo in this patients are unacceptable. I can only only offer palliative RT. Specific Findings: Very limited exercise tolerance \nBaseline sedentary lifestyle many years Multiple admissions for COPD Limited VO2 max, peak Mets, Reduced anaerobic threshold ~35% predicted significant bulk muscle atrophy (CT) clinical exam,'),(2840,485325500,4,'Oligomets I discussed with the patient the investigational nature of SBRT for oligo-metastatic disease. Early data suggests that RT can improve local control and progression free survival in small studies. There is no evidence that SBRT for oligomets can cure or prolong survival. Level 1 evidence is lacking. At the TBCC SBRT for oligomets is offered under a prospective in-house protocol which will gather outcomes and toxicity. All cases are reviewed in SBRT rounds with other radiation oncologists, and the treatment offered is per our local treatment algorithm. The patient understands the limited nature of the evidence and investigative nature of the protocol. The primary goals of therapy would be to potentially slow disease progression locally, and to allow for an interval chemo free period or in the case of oligo-progression Â to allow for the patient to remain on their current chemo. The case was reviwed at SBRT rounds and the reccomendation was to proceed with the standard of care and consider clinical trials of SBRT in the future.'),(2841,485325500,2,'A loop of bowel appears to drape across the tumor within 3 mm. the lesion is also incmpletely imaged on MRI'),(2842,485325500,9,'Incomplete or pending important staging for final decision.. PET scan pending'),(2843,728084900,1,NULL),(2845,999183811,17,'Although he has a significant cardiac history his exercise tolerance is very good with no clear issue with exertional dyspnea/ chest pain'),(2847,817114531,9,'Other.. There is extensive involvement of the stomach - this patient would not tbe a candidate for CROSS. (neo adjuvant CRT followed by surgery). I will leave it to MO or Surgeons to evaluate him for FLOT.'),(2848,728084900,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic.. extensive mediastnal LN, and solitary bony metastasis'),(2849,454079700,9,'Other.. her case was discussed in ARC rounds not eligible for SRS clinical trial.'),(2850,763838820,9,'PET Scan. PET scan was not available at the time of consult. It is not booked. I discussed with the patient that my diagnosis and plan are based on the best information today. I explained that the PET scan may in some cases find cancer which is not detectable on a CT, which could change the diagnosis and overall treatment plan. (Upstaging to Stage 4 disease, or missing treatable nodal disease from the current RT plan). We will best attempt to incorporate or change the plan once the PET results are available. I gave the patient the option of waiting until we have the PET scan, the patient understands and would like to proceed with the current treatment plan without a PET. I will contact the patient with the results of the scan once available.'),(2852,331250920,9,'Unknown primary. we have not been able to identify a primary. Given the predominant disease is below the diaphragm a GI source is suspected. The pathology at this time has not further help identify a particular source.'),(2853,763838820,9,'Surgical Risks. I am conscerned about his BMI and Sleep Apnea as operative risks.'),(2854,619493600,1,'He has modest exercise tolerance. Able to carry a 25 bag of rice up flights of stairs. He walks these stairs several times a day.'),(2855,619493600,9,'PET. PET scan was not available at the time of consult. It appears to be scheduled on sept 10. I discussed with the patient that my diagnosis and plan are based on the best information today. I explained that the PET scan may in some cases find cancer which is not detectable on a CT, which could change the diagnosis