unds and there will be consideration for the MWA study with combined SBRT and MWA approach.'),(2860,257053510,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy.. Variceal bleeds are relative contra indication for SBRT - as it can increase risk of GI Bleed. He has not has any bleeds in the last 1 year. No recent scopes. Non ongoing vomiting from any other reason'),(2861,578873130,9,'RAPIDO. The patient has been screened for RAPIDO (5x5 RT ? Chemo ? Surgery): T4a, cT4b, extramural vascular invasion (EMVI+). N2, Positive MRF, i.e. tumor or lymph node < 1 mm from the mesorectal fascia. Enlarged lateral nodes, > 1 cm (lat LN+). I discussed with the patient the emerging evidence for this treatment that has reduced toxicity, improved distant mets and comparable local control to the current standard of care. It also save the patient trips and time 5# vs 25#. We discussed the pros and cons of this treatment vs the standard of care. I also discussed this option with their surgeon and medical oncology team.  Specific indication: MRF 1mm'),(2862,119061010,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic.. this is a massive 11 cm tumor extending from the Hilm to the chest wall. This precludes curative intent RT based on size alone'),(2863,119061010,9,'Medically inoperable.. detailed consult from Dr Grondin.'),(2864,429630800,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy.. Patient cannot lay FLAT'),(2865,429630800,9,'Limited Pulmonary reserve for radiation.. Currently his cardiac and pulmonary status preclude RT.'),(2866,429630800,9,'Medically inoperable.. based on my clinical evaluation. But we do not have a formal surgical opinion.'),(2867,888335110,9,'Other.. Although the pathology is suggesting a possible Gi colonic source in a patient with an irregular liver mass, known cirrhosis and hep C - I still think that HCC is high n the differential. Biopsy was from the met - which may be more undifferentiated than the primary.'),(2868,907170390,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic.. The tumor abuts the stomach which will limit RT doses. The tumor is also quite large - and may benefit from systemic downstaging prior to SBRT'),(2869,907170390,9,'Other.. I discussed with the patient the investigational nature of SBRT for cholangio ca. Early data suggests that RT can improve local control and progression free survival in small studies. There is no evidence that SBRT cure or prolong survival. Level 1 evidence is lacking. At the TBCC SBRT is offered under a prospective in-house protocol which will gather outcomes and toxicity. All cases are reviewed in SBRT rounds with other radiation oncologists, and the treatment offered is per our local treatment algorithm. The patient understands the limited nature of the evidence and investigative nature of the protocol. The primary goals of therapy would be to potentially slow disease progression locally, and to allow for an interval chemo free period or in the case of oligo-progression Â to allow for the patient to remain on their current chemo.'),(2870,907170390,9,'Other.. Child Pugh score is B7 - which may preclude systemic therapy.'),(2871,309094700,9,'Suspicious findings of metastatic disease outside possible radiation fields.. Lung nodule'),(2872,309094700,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic.. Locally advanced disease with invasion into the trachea precludes radical CRT - fistula risk.'),(2873,309094700,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy.. metallic stents in the trachea are a contraindication for Radical CRT to the esophagus - due to high risk of perforation. Only palliative doses may be used in this setting.'),(2874,735080120,9,'Other.. Although the segment 7 lesion is amenable to RFA the segment 1 lesion will be difficult to address. We will attempt to SBRT both sites'),(2875,348065000,1,NULL),(2876,735080120,1,'he is quite frail immobile and many comorbidities. I would be cauti